Often, the Hiragana and Katakana are fairly similar, so learning them at the same time is fairly easy.<br>
You should be able to knock off both alphabets in one or two afternoons.<br>
<br>
(Kanji, on the other hand, is strictly for crazy people who don't mind dedicating the next several years to a monk-like lifesytle of memorizing thousands of dense scribbles.  Yccch-ptui !)<br>
<br>
Here's my hiragana/katakana site.  Should put things in a fun way.<br>
Check it out:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/hiragana1.html">www.fureai-ch.ne.jp/~seth/hiragana1.html</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
This tutorial is different from most, because it doesn't just throw a bunch of shapes at you, and say &quot;Here... learn this&quot;.<br>
Instead, it gives you a REASON to associate a particular shape with a particular sound.<br>
<br>
The character for AH, for example, looks a heck of alot like a guy sitting in a hot-tub and saying &quot;Aaaaaahhhhh.&quot;<br>
<br>
The character for KA looks a little like a CAt.  (KA = CA)...get it ?<br>
<br>
When reading through the site, feel free to skip over the wordy intro, and go straight to the cartoony bits that start about a third of the way down the page, which are good fun.<br>
